Understanding the European Football by Jorge Saldivar

In this study, I analyze football (soccer in US) events through a dataset composed of 941009 events collected from 9,074 european games. The dataset is open source and available to download at https://www.kaggle.com/secareanualin/football-events. Each event has information about the type of event (11 types, including foul, corner, offside, and red card), the side of the team involved in the event (home or away), the location of the event in the pitch (e.g., defensive half, attacking half, penalty spot), the game situation in which the event happens (e.g., open play, corner, free kick). If the event is a shot, the dataset provides also information of the shot place (e.g., bottom left corner, top left corner, center of the goal), the shot outcome (e.g., on target, off target, blocked), the part of the body involved in the shot (i.e., left foot, right foot, head), the method used to assist the shoter (e.g., pass, cross, headed pass), and a boolean variable that indicates whether the shot ends up as a goal. There are complementary data about the events such as the team that generates the event or the players involved but in this analysis I will concentrate in the nine features presented before. As an example, the first five rows are shown below.

Univariate Plots Section

Event Types

The figure above help us to have a first overview on the primary characteristics of the European football. Fouls and free kicks are the two most common events in games, followed by goal attempts — they represent 50% of the events in the dataset. The large occurrence of fouls and free kicks demonstrates that games are apparently not fluent but frenquently interrupted by ilegal plays and the resulting direct or indirect kicks. It is interesting to notice that even when fouls are among the most common events, games are characterized by fair plays considering the low frequency of yellow and red cards (4.4% of the total events). The figure shows that corners are not that common, which seems to indicate that goal attempts come more from open plays (e.g., give and go) than through set pieces. The low occurrence of penalties (0.3% of the total events) indicates that fouls are committed outside the goal area.

Side

The amount events per side are balanace between those related with home teams (51.9%) and the ones belonged to away teams.

Location

Less than half of the record (49.6%) have registered the location of pitch where the event happened. The records with blank location were not included in the figure above. Some results in this figure might complement the insights obtained in the analysis of the event types. For example, fouls might occurre in the majority of cases in the defensive half and probably outside of the box. However, further analyses are required to better understand relationship between variables.
